## Summary of All Fixes

| # | Location | Bug | Fix |
|---|----------|-----|-----|
| 1 | `runJitNds` | Uses `getPC()` (pipelined) instead of actual fetch PC | Add `getActualPC()`, use it |
| 2 | `emit_call` | Uses r12 (`PPC_TMP3`), volatile and shared | Use r29 as `PPC_CALL_TMP`, save in frame |
| 3 | `FRAME_*` constants | Frame too small for r14..r29, `FRAME_REGSYNC` too small | Resize to 176, adjust `FRAME_REGSYNC` to 80 |
| 4 | Branch emitters | Taken path lacks `emit_epilogue`, falls through to corrupt code | Add `emit_epilogue` after each `emit_syncToInterp` in branch paths |
| 5 | Fallback handler | Interpreter fallback may branch, but block continues sequential | Set `blockEnded = true` after `emit_interpFallback` |
| 6 | `JitPpc_syncToInterp` | Writes raw address to `*registers[15]`, bypassing pipeline | Call `interp->setPC()` for R15 to flush pipeline properly |
| 7 | `compileBlock` | Final `emit_syncToInterp/epilogue` redundant when block has explicit return | Add `hasExplicitReturn` flag to `EmitCtx` |

The ISI exception specifically is caused by bugs **1** (wrong PC → compiling/executing wrong block, possibly non-code memory) and **4** (taken branch path falls through to wrong code, eventually jumping to an ARM address as if it were PPC). Fix these two first and you should eliminate the ISI.
